metadata.name: CrossWorlds #304
metadata.description:
In 2057 an error occurred in the particle accelerator machine causing a diversion in space-time that leads to duplication of our world. Scientists discovered that they can travel to these "CrossWorlds" with wormholes plagued by singularities occurring at weakened points of the fabric between worlds. In time, some worlds became hostile to each other, tried to plunder their natural resources, and take over civilizations but other worlds learned how to co-exist peacefully...
------------------
Animation_
Press R: Rotates the world 180Â°
Idle: Default animation cycles from corner to corner
Mouse: Cursor-dependent animation
MobileDevice: Controls the animation with the orientation of the device. (Android only)
------------------
Live-view_
Resolution: Add "&res=" end of your url with a resolution multiplier. (0.5-6)
Press S: Saves the current scene (Default 1600x1600 px).
Press L: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as PNG.
Press D: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as SVG.
------------------
Created with p5js.

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #266
metadata.description:
â€œSouthern Gothicâ€ is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

â€œSouthern Gothicâ€ borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery Oâ€™Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: MONOLITH #146
metadata.description:
Very limited facts are known about these strange monolithic structures. Black, rectilinear, similar to obsidian stone but made of strange materials. According to legend, an ancient civilization of high intelligence, called the Explorers of Latent Space, distributed hundreds of monoliths throughout time and space in order to study the behavior of species in the infinite Universe.

Some say that it is the divine intelligence of God. Others say that, in spite of their objectual and material condition, the monoliths possess their own consciousness and an intelligence beyond the natural and artificial. Their purpose or objective, to this day, remains a mystery.

_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_

this work is done only with code, using threejs and p5js
it might be a bit slow on low-end devices, be patient

metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #882
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of â€‹â€‹the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: Uplands #5
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Uplands' is a striking design that plays with color and perspective.

The result resembles an aerial view of neon fields stretching into the distance!

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: Ex Mobius (Vintage Red) #16
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

Each output in this collection has the same "mobius" shape, but the number and positions of the colored regions varies.

All outputs in this collection will have the same color palette (called Vintage Red).

Please allow up to 20 seconds for each image to fully load.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x1500px PNG.

Several "Ex Mobius" collections will be released, each with a different color palette.
